when some things are uncertain

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:46.600
and others are more certain?

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:48.820
Or sometimes good things
happen, sometimes not.

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:51.610
And there's a probability
distribution over those events.

00:00:51.610 --> 00:00:53.620
And how does that affect
how you make choices?

00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:55.120
And social
preferences is what we

00:00:55.120 --> 00:00:57.820
talked about during the
last few weeks, which

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:01.420
is how does the presence of
others affect our choices?

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:03.370
How much do we
care about others?

00:01:03.370 --> 00:01:06.350
And do we decide or
make choices differently

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:08.270
if others are involved?

00:01:08.270 --> 00:01:09.910
So now what we've
done with preferences

00:01:09.910 --> 00:01:13.570
is sometimes saying
we have our models

00:01:13.570 --> 00:01:17.233
to think of ways to think
about what makes people happy.

00:01:17.233 --> 00:01:19.150
The second part when you
try to make decisions

00:01:19.150 --> 00:01:22.220
is when you look at your
environment, what are prices

00:01:22.220 --> 00:01:22.720
like?

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:26.180
What do we know about others?

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:27.160
What are our beliefs?

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:28.210
And what do we attend to?

00:01:28.210 --> 00:01:30.170
And how do we learn when
we get new information?

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:31.462
So what information do we have?

00:01:31.462 --> 00:01:34.180
And what information
do we attend to?

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:38.420
And how do we learn when we get
new information given to us?

00:01:38.420 --> 00:01:41.440
And so we're going to
talk first about attention

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:42.130
in this lecture.

00:01:42.130 --> 00:01:44.170
And then the next
couple of times, we're

00:01:44.170 --> 00:01:49.003
going to talk about
beliefs and learning.

00:01:49.003 --> 00:01:50.420
So what we're going
to do today is

00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:52.295
we're going to talk
about three broad issues.

00:01:52.295 --> 00:01:55.240
One is going to provide you
some motivating evidence

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:57.580
about attention.

00:01:57.580 --> 00:02:00.700
We had a little bit on
this in lectures 1 and 2.

00:02:00.700 --> 00:02:02.805
But I wanted to remind
you of that a little bit.

00:02:02.805 --> 00:02:04.930
Then we're going to talk
about two specific papers.

00:02:04.930 --> 00:02:07.510
One is a pretty famous
paper by Raj Chetty

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:10.900
and co-authors on
inattention to taxes.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:13.660
And then you're going to talk
about a second paper, which

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:15.687
is learning by noticing.

00:02:15.687 --> 00:02:17.770
In particular, we're going
to ask the question of,

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:21.430
how is it possible that people
do not attend to things that

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:23.950
are important in their lives?

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:26.590
You might say, well, if
attention is limited,

00:02:26.590 --> 00:02:27.650
that's all good.

00:02:27.650 --> 00:02:30.340
But then we should
expect that people attend

00:02:30.340 --> 00:02:31.740
to really important stuff.

00:02:31.740 --> 00:02:34.690
So some sort of rational
inattention models

00:02:34.690 --> 00:02:36.880
would say, well, it
might well be that people

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:38.620
are inattentive in some ways.

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:42.835
But really, it can't be
possibly that the welfare

00:02:42.835 --> 00:02:44.380
losses from
inattention are large

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:46.300
because if they were
large, if there's things

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:47.758
that people missed,
then they would

00:02:47.758 --> 00:02:50.530
pay attention to those things
and shift their attention

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:51.260
optimally.

00:02:51.260 --> 00:02:54.100
The learning by
noticing paper is

00:02:54.100 --> 00:02:56.110
one theory, at
least potentially,

00:02:56.110 --> 00:03:00.070
that addresses this question.

00:03:00.070 --> 00:03:05.800
The way these movie perception
tests work is, essentially,

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:08.210
they look for what's
called change blindness.

00:03:08.210 --> 00:03:10.810
So the way this works
is, often, there's

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:12.910
one actor, which
is this guy here.

00:03:12.910 --> 00:03:15.250
I think you can see
probably right now there's

00:03:15.250 --> 00:03:17.800
some guy who does some activity.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:19.600
You're supposed
to watch the guy.

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:24.040
And then there's a second
scene in some ways where

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:26.740
the person does something else.

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:29.200
In this case, the guy--

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:31.030
sorry, where is he?

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:32.800
The guy is taking a phone call.

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:34.360
And so what happens then is--

00:03:37.330 --> 00:03:39.260
essentially, then, this
guy that you see here

00:03:39.260 --> 00:03:42.890
that takes a phone call is a
different person altogether.

00:03:42.890 --> 00:03:45.040
And so that's called
change blindness

00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:47.380
where, essentially,
people then tend

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:49.480
to not notice at
all that there's two

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:51.910
different people in a scene.

00:03:51.910 --> 00:03:53.410
There's other types
of experiments

00:03:53.410 --> 00:03:54.610
that do this, as well.

00:03:54.610 --> 00:03:57.700
One version of that would
be people who go to a bank.

00:03:57.700 --> 00:03:58.750
There's a bank teller.

00:03:58.750 --> 00:04:00.850
And this is like all
psych experiments.

00:04:00.850 --> 00:04:01.810
There's a bank teller.

00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:06.925
Here's the other guy.

00:04:06.925 --> 00:04:07.800
Here's the other guy.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:08.800
So you see this guy.

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.842
He looks actually very
different to the other guy

00:04:10.842 --> 00:04:12.068
that you had seen before.

00:04:12.068 --> 00:04:13.110
So people go to the bank.

00:04:13.110 --> 00:04:13.830
There's a bank teller.

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:15.332
The bank teller
says, oh, yeah, I'll

00:04:15.332 --> 00:04:17.040
have to just get
something from the back.

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:19.019
And then another
person shows up who's

00:04:19.019 --> 00:04:21.750
a totally different person,
often looks very different,

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:23.610
sometimes wears
different things.

00:04:23.610 --> 00:04:25.900
And people just
don't notice at all.

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:27.480
And that's sort of
type of experiment

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:32.030
is called change blindness.

00:04:32.030 --> 00:04:34.670
I've already shown you
the gorilla test before.

00:04:34.670 --> 00:04:37.170
I'm going to not play it again
because I've already seen it.

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:38.670
But essentially,
it's the same where

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:40.290
people are asked
to pay attention

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:44.640
to how many passes people
play in a basketball game.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:47.100
And then there's a
guy who's in a gorilla

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:53.010
suit who shows up and walks
through the whole screen.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:57.080
And many people just
miss the gorilla suit.

00:04:57.080 --> 00:04:59.830
Now, what's going on here?

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:03.290
There is a large number of
these types of experiments.

00:05:03.290 --> 00:05:08.540
They're called change blindness
or inattention experiments.

00:05:08.540 --> 00:05:10.950
And there's another
version of that,

00:05:10.950 --> 00:05:13.470
which is called the dichotic
listening experiment.

00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:17.930
This is going back
to broadband, 1958.

00:05:17.930 --> 00:05:21.020
They essentially look
something like this

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:25.820
where there's people who wear
headphones with messages.

00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:28.880
On the one hand, on
our left, there's

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:30.420
supposed to be ignored inputs.

00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:33.020
And on the other hand, there's
supposed to be attended inputs.

00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:34.490
So the person in
the experiment is

00:05:34.490 --> 00:05:37.130
asked, only listen to
stuff that's, I guess,

00:05:37.130 --> 00:05:39.620
in your left ear.

00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:41.390
These are the attended inputs.

00:05:41.390 --> 00:05:44.370
I'm going to ask you some
questions about that.

00:05:44.370 --> 00:05:46.730
And then what you're
supposed to then do is--

00:05:52.447 --> 00:05:53.280
are you still stuck?

00:05:57.530 --> 00:05:58.220
This is bad.

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:01.220
One second.

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:04.790
I'm going to unshare my screen.

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:05.690
Exactly.

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:07.090
Give me a second.

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:11.870
So the way this works is you
would have headphones on.

00:06:11.870 --> 00:06:15.470
And on one hand, you
hear inputs that you're

00:06:15.470 --> 00:06:16.740
supposed to attend to.

00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:18.350
On the other ear,
you hear inputs

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:20.150
that you're not
supposed to attend to.

00:06:20.150 --> 00:06:28.810
And usually, then, you
get explicit instructions

00:06:28.810 --> 00:06:30.730
to attend to the
message in one ear

00:06:30.730 --> 00:06:33.190
and then asked later about
message in the other ear.

00:06:33.190 --> 00:06:35.110
People can't remember it.

00:06:35.110 --> 00:06:37.720
And then what these
experiments often are--

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.520
when asked to keep a
number in their head,

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:41.660
people remember the
played message much less.

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:45.850
So essentially, what this
shows is that, A, I guess,

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:49.240
people are pretty good at
shifting attention in some way.

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:51.640
But attention is
limited to the extent

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:54.190
of when you're also supposed
to attend to something

00:06:54.190 --> 00:06:55.750
else at the same time.

00:06:55.750 --> 00:06:57.580
It's essentially
too much going on,

00:06:57.580 --> 00:07:01.380
and it's really hard for
you to remember everything.

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:05.540
And so to some degree,
it tells us, A, I guess,

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:07.150
attention is limited.

00:07:07.150 --> 00:07:08.240
We tend to focus--

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:09.680
when instructed,
at least, we tend

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:11.840
to focus on stuff
that's important, right?

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:13.465
So like in the
broadband experiment,

00:07:13.465 --> 00:07:15.590
if I tell you listen to
the stuff in the right ear,

00:07:15.590 --> 00:07:17.030
you actually focus
your attention

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:18.350
to the stuff in the right ear.

00:07:18.350 --> 00:07:19.878
You miss the stuff
on the left ear,

00:07:19.878 --> 00:07:21.920
so you can sort of direct
your attention to stuff

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:23.600
that you think is
important or you've

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:25.490
been instructed to focus on.

00:07:25.490 --> 00:07:27.360
So that kind of works.

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:30.800
But at the same time, attention
is limited in the sense of you

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:33.470
can actually not remember
what's in the other ear

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:34.803
because you didn't attend to it.

00:07:34.803 --> 00:07:36.845
So in some sense, it's
not like you automatically

00:07:36.845 --> 00:07:37.490
remember stuff.

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:39.590
You have to pay
attention to things.

00:07:39.590 --> 00:07:42.680
And then at the same time,
when we now exogenously reduce

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:47.150
people's attention
by telling people

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:50.570
to keep a number in their head,
distracting them in some way,

00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:53.300
people are much more--

00:07:53.300 --> 00:07:55.700
even playing the played
message, the message that you're

00:07:55.700 --> 00:07:56.660
supposed to remember.

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:59.720
I'm sure they don't remember
the other message, either.

00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:00.380
OK.

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:04.155
So then in addition, which
I already alluded to,

00:08:04.155 --> 00:08:05.030
attention is limited.

00:08:07.678 --> 00:08:09.470
There might be different
factors that might

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:10.680
affect people's attention.

00:08:10.680 --> 00:08:14.790
So what factors might be
important for attention?

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:16.890
Could be your physical
environment in some ways.

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:18.330
It could be it's really hot.

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:19.730
It could be it's really cold.

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:23.590
It could be other
threats in the room,

00:08:23.590 --> 00:08:30.870
so if you're in some
place where you're

00:08:30.870 --> 00:08:33.700
worried that there will be wild
animals coming anytime soon.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:36.169
Physical environment
could be really important.

00:08:36.169 --> 00:08:39.400
It could be really loud.

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:41.750
Distractions could
be social media.

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:44.560
It could be other
stuff that you're just

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:46.210
trying to do at the same time.

00:08:46.210 --> 00:08:49.540
Maybe you're trying to solve
some problems right now.

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:53.290
Maybe you're trying to prepare
for some-- for example,

00:08:53.290 --> 00:08:55.895
I had a phone call
just before our class.

00:08:55.895 --> 00:08:58.270
And I was also trying to think
about what to do in class,

00:08:58.270 --> 00:08:59.937
and it's just really
distracting to have

00:08:59.937 --> 00:09:02.350
other things you're thinking
about at the same time.

00:09:02.350 --> 00:09:05.260
Could be worries about your
own or others' well being.

00:09:05.260 --> 00:09:08.630
It could be sleep or what
people were saying already,

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:11.830
people's physical environment.

00:09:11.830 --> 00:09:14.450
We're going to talk about some
of this in the poverty lecture.

00:09:14.450 --> 00:09:17.170
So there in
particular, one thing

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:19.120
that poverty tends
to come along with

00:09:19.120 --> 00:09:21.800
is sort of a bunch of
different ways of--

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:25.840
in addition to not having money
and many other deprivations,

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:30.790
poverty tends to come along
with lots of other factors

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:33.190
that might reduce
people's attention.

00:09:33.190 --> 00:09:34.780
And that's to do with sleep.

00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:37.360
It's to do with
exposure to noise.

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:40.990
It's coming with worries
about people's health

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:42.440
and so on and so forth.

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:44.350
There's some question
about practice.

00:09:44.350 --> 00:09:45.940
Can you actually
practice attention?

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:47.315
And there's some
people who would

00:09:47.315 --> 00:09:49.870
argue, at least in education,
maybe at younger ages--

00:09:49.870 --> 00:09:52.240
suppose you sit
kids down and have

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:55.660
them practice focusing on
tasks like multiplications

00:09:55.660 --> 00:09:57.590
or whatever and
do math problems.

00:09:57.590 --> 00:09:59.950
Some of this, some
people would argue,

00:09:59.950 --> 00:10:04.840
in addition to
just helping people

00:10:04.840 --> 00:10:08.980
learn math, actually the numbers
and so on and how to multiply,

00:10:08.980 --> 00:10:11.380
you might also
actually just help

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:15.130
students learn how to focus and
how to pay attention carefully

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:18.640
to things and particularly
sustained attention

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:22.660
and not get distracted
by other things.

00:10:22.660 --> 00:10:24.250
Other distractions,
by the way, also,

00:10:24.250 --> 00:10:25.730
like temptations, for example.

00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:29.290
So if I put a delicious
chocolate cake in front of you

00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:31.323
and have you-- and if
you're really hungry,

00:10:31.323 --> 00:10:32.740
that might be
actually really hard

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:34.180
to pay attention
to whatever else

00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:38.380
you're doing just because that's
really distracting to you.

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:39.080
OK.

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:43.750
And so we're going to,
for now, keep thinking

00:10:43.750 --> 00:10:45.038
about attention being fixed.

00:10:45.038 --> 00:10:47.080
We're going to get back
to the issue of attention

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:50.080
being malleable and
potentially being

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:54.250
depleted by issues such as
poverty at the end in the very

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:54.910
last lecture.

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:56.500
But for now, we're
going to look at--

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:59.230
think about attention
as fixed but limited.

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:00.730
And now we're going
to look at, what

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:04.670
are the consequences of that?

00:11:04.670 --> 00:11:05.263
OK.

00:11:05.263 --> 00:11:06.680
So then one question
you might ask

00:11:06.680 --> 00:11:09.340
is, well, this listening
task that I just showed you

00:11:09.340 --> 00:11:12.440
or when a monkey walks through
some video or the like,

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:14.240
it's a pretty
low-stakes situation.

00:11:14.240 --> 00:11:15.600
Who really cares?

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.630
And one Chicago
view of economics

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:21.560
would be to say, well, these
are just low-stakes situations.

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:25.670
But once stakes are
really high, then people

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:27.298
will surely pay attention.

00:11:27.298 --> 00:11:29.090
And so there's a number
of different papers

00:11:29.090 --> 00:11:30.500
that look at this issue.

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:39.380
But one quite nice example
here is from the stock market,

00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:42.290
arguably an event of
high economic importance

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:45.230
because people make a lot of
money, potentially, from it.

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:47.480
So there's this very nice
people by Huberman and Regev

00:11:47.480 --> 00:11:51.110
from 2001 which has--

