buying some other company
that's actually not

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:00.610
even doing anything anymore.

00:19:00.610 --> 00:19:05.800
So there's lots of stories
about people being inattentive

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:10.530
even in situations when stakes
are really, really high.

00:19:10.530 --> 00:19:13.350
Now, then, you might say,
well, how do we now measure?

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:16.980
So now in some sense we
have some evidence here

00:19:16.980 --> 00:19:19.620
that people are-- in some sense
somewhat informal evidence

00:19:19.620 --> 00:19:21.660
that people are inattentive.

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:25.950
Now, how would you measure the
impact of inattention overall?

00:19:28.490 --> 00:19:30.730
So if you wanted to just
measure and demonstrate

00:19:30.730 --> 00:19:33.340
that people are inattentive,
in addition to what I've just

00:19:33.340 --> 00:19:34.690
shown you, what might you do?

00:19:34.690 --> 00:19:36.960
How might you do that?

00:19:36.960 --> 00:19:40.100
There's some information that
you usually get in the world

00:19:40.100 --> 00:19:41.600
and they should have.

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:45.560
One example that we can discuss
is essentially prices or taxes.

00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:48.320
And now if you want to
demonstrate that people

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:50.720
are actually missing those
prices or taxes, what

00:19:50.720 --> 00:19:53.210
you can do is now you
can make it very salient.

00:19:53.210 --> 00:19:55.220
You make it really
apparent to people.

00:19:55.220 --> 00:20:00.320
And then you can look at, when
you look at changes in prices

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:03.680
or the change of making things
from non-selling to selling,

00:20:03.680 --> 00:20:04.940
how do people react?

00:20:04.940 --> 00:20:07.640
Or maybe you make, for
example, taxes very salient.

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:11.240
What happens to people's
demand for certain products?

00:20:11.240 --> 00:20:15.170
And if then making things
salient changes people's

00:20:15.170 --> 00:20:20.030
behavior, that then identifies
underlying inattention.

00:20:20.030 --> 00:20:21.860
So if you just-- people
don't have access

00:20:21.860 --> 00:20:23.480
to certain information,
in some sense, that's

00:20:23.480 --> 00:20:25.188
less interesting
because that just means,

00:20:25.188 --> 00:20:27.440
well, I don't have
the information

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:29.200
that's really available to me.

00:20:29.200 --> 00:20:30.950
But in some ways, I
could make information

00:20:30.950 --> 00:20:32.330
that's really very salient--

00:20:32.330 --> 00:20:34.700
I essentially could
reduce the salience,

00:20:34.700 --> 00:20:37.250
as you say, of certain types
of information-- again,

00:20:37.250 --> 00:20:39.545
information that should
be available to them.

00:20:39.545 --> 00:20:43.340
For example, suppose I do sales.

00:20:43.340 --> 00:20:46.010
And I'm trying to, as
a company, sell things.

00:20:46.010 --> 00:20:46.850
You go to a store.

00:20:46.850 --> 00:20:49.770
And usually, sales are made
very salient to people.

00:20:49.770 --> 00:20:51.770
Now you could essentially
just change the prices

00:20:51.770 --> 00:20:53.930
without making these
sales very salient.

00:20:53.930 --> 00:20:57.680
And then you could look at, how
attentive are people to that?

00:20:57.680 --> 00:21:00.470
In a way, that's, in some
ways, less natural, right,

00:21:00.470 --> 00:21:03.248
because when people are--

00:21:03.248 --> 00:21:04.790
in a way, what we
want to demonstrate

00:21:04.790 --> 00:21:08.390
is that in people's
real lives, there's

00:21:08.390 --> 00:21:10.730
information available to them.

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:13.940
And they're not really paying
sufficiently much attention

00:21:13.940 --> 00:21:15.000
to it.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:18.200
So if you can then
change that in some ways

00:21:18.200 --> 00:21:20.670
and demonstrate that now
they're changing their behavior,

00:21:20.670 --> 00:21:22.220
that must mean that
previously, they

00:21:22.220 --> 00:21:25.700
had been like misoptimizing.

00:21:25.700 --> 00:21:28.280
If instead you
did something like

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:34.340
if you reduce the salience of
certain types of information,

00:21:34.340 --> 00:21:36.840
that's, in a way, somewhat less
interesting because it would

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:39.898
say, well, it doesn't
really mean that they

00:21:39.898 --> 00:21:41.190
were inattentive to start with.

00:21:41.190 --> 00:21:42.930
It's more like you're hiding
something from people,

00:21:42.930 --> 00:21:43.990
and now they can't find it.

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:45.990
That's, in some ways,
somewhat less interesting.

00:21:45.990 --> 00:21:49.230
But I think in principle,
you'd also, exactly as you say,

00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:51.570
identify inattention.

00:21:51.570 --> 00:21:55.060
So there's a few type of
things that people have done.

00:21:55.060 --> 00:21:57.660
And to be clear, there's
often a pretty fine line

00:21:57.660 --> 00:21:59.778
between attention and memory.

00:21:59.778 --> 00:22:02.070
So one thing we could do is--
and this is what Maya was

00:22:02.070 --> 00:22:03.840
saying previously--

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:07.090
you could make certain features,
like taxes, very salient.

00:22:07.090 --> 00:22:10.010
That's what we're
going to look at next.

00:22:10.010 --> 00:22:13.290
In addition, you could
provide some information

00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:15.420
when the correct response
is known already.

00:22:15.420 --> 00:22:17.378
That's one we're going
to talk about afterwards

00:22:17.378 --> 00:22:19.020
is the study by Hanna et al.

00:22:19.020 --> 00:22:21.150
So that's kind of
like when people

00:22:21.150 --> 00:22:23.310
have certain types of
information already

00:22:23.310 --> 00:22:26.130
but then providing that
information again or giving

00:22:26.130 --> 00:22:28.920
that information in some
sort of concise form

00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:32.670
and potentially notifying
people of the fact

00:22:32.670 --> 00:22:36.190
that this information could
be or should be important.

00:22:36.190 --> 00:22:38.310
And then we now see
people react to it.

00:22:38.310 --> 00:22:41.100
That doesn't mean that that
must mean that, before, they

00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:42.480
were inattentive.

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:45.150
Another thing that people
have done a lot is reminders.

00:22:45.150 --> 00:22:47.972
Reminders often
are sort of like--

00:22:47.972 --> 00:22:49.930
you can think of the
pieces like memory issues,

00:22:49.930 --> 00:22:51.630
and people just forget things.

00:22:51.630 --> 00:22:54.120
But in some sense, memory
issues and attention issues

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:55.505
are very closely linked.

00:22:55.505 --> 00:22:56.880
If you forget
something, then you

00:22:56.880 --> 00:22:58.570
don't pay attention
to something.

00:22:58.570 --> 00:23:00.450
So if I remind you of
something, now you're

00:23:00.450 --> 00:23:02.040
paying attention
to, for example,

00:23:02.040 --> 00:23:05.340
your savings or your medical
adherence, like you should

00:23:05.340 --> 00:23:07.380
take certain drugs and so on.

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:10.050
There's a number of studies that
essentially provide reminders

00:23:10.050 --> 00:23:11.370
to people.

00:23:11.370 --> 00:23:13.800
And if these reminders
have effects,

00:23:13.800 --> 00:23:16.620
then that must mean that people
were not paying attention

00:23:16.620 --> 00:23:19.470
to those kinds of
things, often presumably

00:23:19.470 --> 00:23:20.760
because of memory problems.

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:24.330
They just forget sometimes.

00:23:24.330 --> 00:23:25.140
OK.

