00:24:00.750 --> 00:24:05.130
the consumer, inattentive
consumer perceived

00:24:05.130 --> 00:24:08.040
value-- instead of
perceiving the true value V,

00:24:08.040 --> 00:24:11.010
the consumer perceives
the value of V hat,

00:24:11.010 --> 00:24:13.815
which is little v, which
is a salient component.

00:24:13.815 --> 00:24:15.690
So even if you're
inattentive, the assumption

00:24:15.690 --> 00:24:20.290
is the salient part of
the good you always see.

00:24:20.290 --> 00:24:22.290
For example, what color
is the good or the like?

00:24:22.290 --> 00:24:24.466
You always see that.

00:24:24.466 --> 00:24:28.440
And in addition, the opaque
component, the stuff that's

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:31.050
not salient, you're only
going to pay attention

00:24:31.050 --> 00:24:35.810
to the fraction
of 1 minus theta.

00:24:35.810 --> 00:24:37.890
So the degree of
inattention-- so theta

00:24:37.890 --> 00:24:40.340
is our inattention parameter.

00:24:40.340 --> 00:24:43.230
And theta measures how much
are you paying attention

00:24:43.230 --> 00:24:46.020
to stuff that's not
particularly salient.

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:48.950
So for theta equals 0, you're
back to the cases before.

00:24:48.950 --> 00:24:53.640
For theta equals 0, V hat
equals V, which is essentially

00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:55.360
just a standard case.

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:58.740
If theta were 1-- so theta is
supposed to be between 0 and 1.

00:24:58.740 --> 00:25:00.570
If theta is 1, then
essentially you're

00:25:00.570 --> 00:25:04.490
not paying attention at all
to the opaque component.

00:25:04.490 --> 00:25:06.780
And anywhere in between,
essentially, then, you're

00:25:06.780 --> 00:25:10.630
paying only partial attention
to the opaque component.

00:25:10.630 --> 00:25:16.150
So the interpretation is each
individual essentially sees v--

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:19.770
sorry, sees o to some degree
but processes it only partially

00:25:19.770 --> 00:25:22.620
to the degree of theta.

00:25:22.620 --> 00:25:25.740
Of course, whether you actually
see it and not process it

00:25:25.740 --> 00:25:28.260
or whether you miss it
entirely is, in some sense,

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:29.470
a philosophical question.

00:25:29.470 --> 00:25:32.180
But think about like, everybody
has, at least in principle,

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:34.080
access to the component o.

00:25:34.080 --> 00:25:38.700
But they only process
and pay attention to it

00:25:38.700 --> 00:25:41.610
only to some degree.

00:25:41.610 --> 00:25:42.270
OK.

00:25:42.270 --> 00:25:47.410
So Chetty et al. applies this
model essentially to taxes.

00:25:47.410 --> 00:25:51.150
So one very interesting
feature about some taxes

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:55.080
is the fact that sales taxes
are only added at the register,

00:25:55.080 --> 00:25:56.670
right?

00:25:56.670 --> 00:26:03.300
At least in most cases, you
would shop in the store.

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:05.910
And then the sales tax, only
at the end once you actually

00:26:05.910 --> 00:26:10.620
go to the store, will be added.

00:26:10.620 --> 00:26:13.890
Now, people are not--

00:26:13.890 --> 00:26:14.400
people know.

00:26:14.400 --> 00:26:15.838
When you ask people
directly, what

00:26:15.838 --> 00:26:18.255
is the sales tax in your state,
people actually on average

00:26:18.255 --> 00:26:19.588
are pretty good at knowing this.

00:26:19.588 --> 00:26:22.510
So it's not like people don't
know that there's a sales tax.

00:26:22.510 --> 00:26:24.900
But they might just
forget that there

00:26:24.900 --> 00:26:28.380
are sales taxes for goods.

00:26:28.380 --> 00:26:32.550
So now what you can do now
is you can compare the demand

00:26:32.550 --> 00:26:38.340
response to sales tax changes
versus the demand response

00:26:38.340 --> 00:26:40.050
to other price changes, right?

00:26:40.050 --> 00:26:44.640
So if you see prices
fluctuating in a store over time

00:26:44.640 --> 00:26:48.240
or across goods,
presumably, everybody

00:26:48.240 --> 00:26:50.280
sees those price
changes overall,

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:53.160
if these are price
changes that are not

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:55.050
related to sales
taxes, the reason

00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:58.257
being once you're in the store,
you're going to look at prices.

00:26:58.257 --> 00:27:00.090
You're going to see is
the price high or low

00:27:00.090 --> 00:27:01.560
even before you go
to the register.

00:27:01.560 --> 00:27:05.160
So presumably, you see the
price tag pretty much most

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:06.310
of the time.

00:27:06.310 --> 00:27:09.900
In contrast, when you
look at sales tax changes,

00:27:09.900 --> 00:27:12.750
if the sales taxes
go up for some reason

00:27:12.750 --> 00:27:16.290
or if there's a sales tax
for some items versus others,

00:27:16.290 --> 00:27:19.410
you might just miss
that at the time

00:27:19.410 --> 00:27:22.350
when you're choosing your goods
before you go to the register.

00:27:22.350 --> 00:27:24.120
And once you're then
at the register,

00:27:24.120 --> 00:27:27.810
you might not even notice that
you have paid the sales tax.

00:27:27.810 --> 00:27:29.490
Or you might be
surprised and just don't

00:27:29.490 --> 00:27:34.540
change your behavior any
more but at least notice it.

00:27:34.540 --> 00:27:36.010
So now what did
Chetty et al. do?

00:27:36.010 --> 00:27:39.610
They have data on the demand
for items in a grocery store.

00:27:39.610 --> 00:27:44.830
And they have essentially
the demand, D of V hat.

00:27:44.830 --> 00:27:47.648
Remember, V hat is the function
of the perceived value,

00:27:47.648 --> 00:27:48.940
which I showed you here before.

00:27:48.940 --> 00:27:50.340
Let me go back for a second.

00:27:50.340 --> 00:27:52.450
So you see V hat
here is v, which

00:27:52.450 --> 00:27:55.750
is the salient component,
plus 1 minus theta times o

00:27:55.750 --> 00:27:57.710
as the opaque component.

00:27:57.710 --> 00:28:02.380
So the demand for goods depends
on the perceived value, V hat,

00:28:02.380 --> 00:28:03.890
that people have.

00:28:03.890 --> 00:28:07.600
And there's a visible
part as the value V, which

00:28:07.600 --> 00:28:09.500
is inclusive of the price.

00:28:09.500 --> 00:28:11.735
So when you look at
when you're in a store,

00:28:11.735 --> 00:28:12.610
you look at the good.

00:28:12.610 --> 00:28:13.300
You see the good.

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:14.467
You see whether you like it.

00:28:14.467 --> 00:28:15.340
You see the brand.

00:28:15.340 --> 00:28:17.600
You see the color and
so on and so forth.

00:28:17.600 --> 00:28:20.680
You also see the
price, so the valuation

00:28:20.680 --> 00:28:23.592
that you give or the value
V that you draw from that

00:28:23.592 --> 00:28:25.300
is essentially telling
how much they want

00:28:25.300 --> 00:28:29.860
to have this thing minus
the price that you see,

00:28:29.860 --> 00:28:32.890
which goes into the visible
part of your valuation.

00:28:32.890 --> 00:28:34.670
And then there's a
less visible part,

00:28:34.670 --> 00:28:36.820
which is just stuff
that's essentially hidden.

00:28:36.820 --> 00:28:39.430
And there's a bunch of
different parts to that

00:28:39.430 --> 00:28:41.320
that you might not
pay attention to,

00:28:41.320 --> 00:28:44.260
which could be
ingredients or the like,

00:28:44.260 --> 00:28:46.460
or was it organic
or not and the like.

00:28:46.460 --> 00:28:48.670
But in particular,
the sales tax, right?

00:28:48.670 --> 00:28:51.190
So if you think
about your valuation,

00:28:51.190 --> 00:28:52.810
you would have to
essentially, however

00:28:52.810 --> 00:28:54.880
much you like the
good-- you have

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:57.850
to subtract the
sales tax because you

00:28:57.850 --> 00:29:00.290
have to pay taxes on that good.

00:29:00.290 --> 00:29:02.990
And that's less
visible to some people.

00:29:02.990 --> 00:29:05.660
So you might not
pay attention to it.

00:29:05.660 --> 00:29:10.990
So in this case, it'll be V hat
is v, the visible component,

00:29:10.990 --> 00:29:12.320
plus 1 minus theta times o.

00:29:12.320 --> 00:29:15.280
And that's just repeating
what I showed you before.

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:19.810
And that equals v minus
1 minus theta times tp,

00:29:19.810 --> 00:29:21.610
which is the sales tax.

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:25.840
And now to the extent that
people pay attention to theta,

00:29:25.840 --> 00:29:30.370
the sales tax might
matter more or less.

00:29:30.370 --> 00:29:32.620
There might be other
opaque components

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:35.082
that are unobservable
both to the experimenter

00:29:35.082 --> 00:29:36.040
but also to the person.

00:29:36.040 --> 00:29:37.310
They can abstract from that.

00:29:37.310 --> 00:29:39.727
So for now, they can essentially
say the less visible part

00:29:39.727 --> 00:29:43.090
is only the state tax.

00:29:43.090 --> 00:29:45.070
OK.

00:29:45.070 --> 00:29:46.120
Any questions on this?

00:29:51.110 --> 00:29:52.010
OK.

00:29:52.010 --> 00:29:54.320
So now, and this
is sort of like--

00:29:54.320 --> 00:29:58.010
so now, essentially,
what this gives us now,

00:29:58.010 --> 00:30:01.370
we can essentially try
to see if we have this--

00:30:03.950 --> 00:30:06.440
how can we identify
this parameter theta

00:30:06.440 --> 00:30:08.750
by making things very salient?

00:30:08.750 --> 00:30:13.510
And so the idea is now to
make the tax fully salient.

00:30:13.510 --> 00:30:15.783
Let me show you how this
looks like in practice.

00:30:15.783 --> 00:30:16.450
Here's the math.

00:30:16.450 --> 00:30:18.300
But I'll go back to
this in a second.

00:30:18.300 --> 00:30:22.130
Let me just show you what this
looks like in the experiment.

00:30:22.130 --> 00:30:24.760
So the idea in the
experiment is to say--

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:29.200
you see on the lower part
here, you see a normal price.

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:30.940
You see an original
price tag here.

00:30:30.940 --> 00:30:33.120
This is what the price tag
usually would look like.

00:30:33.120 --> 00:30:34.240
So this would be an item.

00:30:34.240 --> 00:30:37.360
I guess this is brushes.

00:30:37.360 --> 00:30:41.357
This item would
cost $5.79 usually.

00:30:41.357 --> 00:30:43.065
And then what they
did in the experiment,

00:30:43.065 --> 00:30:45.910
they essentially added a tag
where they said, now here,

00:30:45.910 --> 00:30:49.240
%5.79 plus sales tax is $6.22.

00:30:49.240 --> 00:30:51.190
And now they make
it entirely salient

00:30:51.190 --> 00:30:53.510
that there's a sales
tax, and you make

00:30:53.510 --> 00:30:56.070
the true price very salient.

00:30:56.070 --> 00:30:56.570
OK.

00:30:56.570 --> 00:30:57.945
And now the question
is if you do

00:30:57.945 --> 00:31:05.350
that, if we go from theta
being, for example, say 5.5,

00:31:05.350 --> 00:31:09.100
you only partially
observe the sales tax.

00:31:09.100 --> 00:31:12.970
If you go from that to making
the sales tax fully salient,

00:31:12.970 --> 00:31:15.010
what happens to people's demand?

00:31:15.010 --> 00:31:19.780
And can you infer from that
theta, what theta actually

00:31:19.780 --> 00:31:20.560
looks like?

00:31:20.560 --> 00:31:22.270
So let me go back to this.

00:31:22.270 --> 00:31:25.180
So essentially, what
we're trying to look at,

00:31:25.180 --> 00:31:28.480
we're trying to look
at a change in demand

00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:30.460
when theta falls to 0.

00:31:30.460 --> 00:31:31.750
Why does theta fall to 0?

00:31:31.750 --> 00:31:33.280
The assumption here
is that whatever

00:31:33.280 --> 00:31:35.770
is theta people have before,
so you might partially

00:31:35.770 --> 00:31:38.740
or even not at all--

00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:42.220
theta might be 0.5 or 1
or whatever for people.

00:31:42.220 --> 00:31:43.870
But now the
intervention that I just

00:31:43.870 --> 00:31:46.330
showed you brings
theta down to 0, right?

00:31:46.330 --> 00:31:48.520
Because now it's fully
salient to people

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:50.200
what the sales tax is.

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:52.420
And so the question
is now, can we

00:31:52.420 --> 00:31:54.670
have an expression for
the change in log demand

00:31:54.670 --> 00:32:00.880
when theta falls from whatever
it is before down to 0?

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:05.260
So now what we have is
the change in log demand

00:32:05.260 --> 00:32:11.385
is the demand that
we had before.

00:32:11.385 --> 00:32:12.760
This is what I
showed you before.

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:15.370
This was essentially demand
as a function of V. Remember

00:32:15.370 --> 00:32:16.620
what I showed you here before.

00:32:16.620 --> 00:32:17.412
Give me one second.

00:32:17.412 --> 00:32:18.270
I'll go back.

00:32:18.270 --> 00:32:20.910
So what I showed you here,
demand is a function of V hat.

00:32:20.910 --> 00:32:22.350
And V hat is this animal here.

00:32:22.350 --> 00:32:26.070
It's v minus 1 minus
theta times tp.

00:32:26.070 --> 00:32:29.190
Now, the question is, what
happens to demand when

00:32:29.190 --> 00:32:30.987
or log demand here--
forget about the log.

00:32:30.987 --> 00:32:32.070
It's not that interesting.

00:32:32.070 --> 00:32:33.570
That's just for math.

00:32:33.570 --> 00:32:36.830
So here's the demand as a
function of what it was before.

00:32:36.830 --> 00:32:39.420
And here's demand
when I now make

00:32:39.420 --> 00:32:41.010
things very salient, right?

00:32:41.010 --> 00:32:43.490
So now here in this
case, theta equals 0.

00:32:43.490 --> 00:32:46.945
And here, theta is
whatever it had before.

00:32:46.945 --> 00:32:48.570
Now when you have
this expression, what

00:32:48.570 --> 00:32:52.650
you can do is you can linearize
that, take the derivative

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:56.195
and say, what is
this difference?

00:32:56.195 --> 00:32:58.320
Well, this difference is--
and you can do the math.

00:32:58.320 --> 00:33:02.640
It's essentially theta times tp.

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:04.440
And then here, this
is the derivative

00:33:04.440 --> 00:33:05.790
with respect to theta.

00:33:05.790 --> 00:33:08.700
And what this gives
you essentially

00:33:08.700 --> 00:33:12.210
is that the change in log
demand is a function of theta,

00:33:12.210 --> 00:33:14.640
a function of tau,
which is like the tax,

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:19.060
and eta, which is
the price elasticity.

00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:22.260
So essentially, that's to say
if you have now an intervention,

00:33:22.260 --> 00:33:25.470
we can look at, how does
demand or log demand change

00:33:25.470 --> 00:33:27.060
when we do this
intervention, assuming

00:33:27.060 --> 00:33:29.280
that this intervention
brings theta from whatever

00:33:29.280 --> 00:33:31.740
it was before down to 0?

00:33:31.740 --> 00:33:33.930
We can look at now
what happens to demand.

00:33:33.930 --> 00:33:35.550
That's delta log demand here.

00:33:35.550 --> 00:33:37.123
That's just a definition.

00:33:37.123 --> 00:33:38.040
And you can have that.

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:42.900
That's an expression of how we
can relate that to theta to t,

00:33:42.900 --> 00:33:46.170
which is like the taxes--
it is at something like 7%--

00:33:46.170 --> 00:33:49.570
and then eta, which is the
price elasticity of demand.

00:33:49.570 --> 00:33:52.170
So that is to say, if we have
this change in demand that we

00:33:52.170 --> 00:33:54.630
observe from changing
theta down to 0

00:33:54.630 --> 00:33:58.740
and if we had the price
elasticity from just

00:33:58.740 --> 00:34:01.540
other variation in prices
that we see in the world

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:04.740
and if you have t, which is
just how much the tax is,

00:34:04.740 --> 00:34:08.130
that would allow us
to identify theta.

00:34:08.130 --> 00:34:11.010
And that's what the
experiment is trying to do.

00:34:11.010 --> 00:34:13.560
So that implies essentially--
so we can just rearrange this.

00:34:13.560 --> 00:34:18.330
We can just say theta is, just
sort of rearranging things,

00:34:18.330 --> 00:34:22.860
minus the change in log demand
from this intervention divided

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:26.389
by t times the price elasticity.

00:34:26.389 --> 00:34:28.699
OK, and that is just
to say essentially

00:34:28.699 --> 00:34:32.090
what we're trying to see is,
intuitively, that's just to say

00:34:32.090 --> 00:34:35.690
once we make things very salient
going from things not being

00:34:35.690 --> 00:34:38.449
salient to start with to
making things very salient,

00:34:38.449 --> 00:34:41.610
how much does
demand change there?

00:34:41.610 --> 00:34:48.270
And then we can
look at, well, for--

00:34:48.270 --> 00:34:52.480
in this case, I guess, this is
the taxes made very salient.

00:34:52.480 --> 00:34:54.219
And then we can
look at, well, how

00:34:54.219 --> 00:34:55.840
does this compare
to other changes

00:34:55.840 --> 00:34:58.870
in prices, assuming that
essentially people are paying

00:34:58.870 --> 00:35:00.580
attention to prices anyway?

00:35:00.580 --> 00:35:05.290
So if you look at things
becoming more expensive by 1%,

00:35:05.290 --> 00:35:08.470
how much are people changing
their behavior there?

00:35:08.470 --> 00:35:11.800
And now we have to take into
account that what's being

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:13.750
made salient here is the tax t.

00:35:13.750 --> 00:35:16.480
And from backing out the
relative changes in demand

00:35:16.480 --> 00:35:19.810
for usual price changes
versus making things salient,

00:35:19.810 --> 00:35:22.750
we can now try to measure
theta as how much did they

00:35:22.750 --> 00:35:24.830
pay attention before.

00:35:24.830 --> 00:35:28.870
So one way to say this is for
example, if we make things very

00:35:28.870 --> 00:35:30.930
salient and the
change in log demand

00:35:30.930 --> 00:35:33.320
did not-- there's no
change in log demand,

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:36.050
what does that imply for theta?

00:35:36.050 --> 00:35:37.300
What would we learn from that?

00:35:37.300 --> 00:35:39.105
So what was the change
here in demand at 0?

00:35:39.105 --> 00:35:40.730
People did not change
the demand at all

00:35:40.730 --> 00:35:42.760
when you make
things very salient

00:35:42.760 --> 00:35:44.980
versus what it was before.

00:35:44.980 --> 00:35:48.130
Or put differently, if
theta equals 0 here,

00:35:48.130 --> 00:35:52.270
then these two expressions are
the same, which essentially

00:35:52.270 --> 00:35:55.180
means that this thing here
is also going to be 0.

00:35:55.180 --> 00:36:01.750
So essentially, to the extent
that our intervention induces

00:36:01.750 --> 00:36:10.030
large changes in demand, that
must mean that essentially,

00:36:10.030 --> 00:36:14.010
people were very
attentive to start with.

00:36:14.010 --> 00:36:16.200
Essentially, if I'm making
the prices very salient

00:36:16.200 --> 00:36:20.310
and nothing happens, well,
that means people were already

00:36:20.310 --> 00:36:22.590
paying attention before.

00:36:22.590 --> 00:36:25.710
Now, in the maximum
case, if people

00:36:25.710 --> 00:36:29.760
were paying no attention
to prices before,

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:31.120
what would happen then?

00:36:31.120 --> 00:36:33.870
Well, in that case, I
guess-- oops, sorry.

00:36:33.870 --> 00:36:36.660
In that case, theta would be 1.

00:36:36.660 --> 00:36:38.490
So essentially, it
would just be going

00:36:38.490 --> 00:36:41.730
from-- we would look at what's
the demand or change in demand

00:36:41.730 --> 00:36:46.380
from going v minus tp to
v, which is essentially

00:36:46.380 --> 00:36:48.900
just a change in tp.

00:36:48.900 --> 00:36:55.080
So that would be essentially
say if the tax was 7%, now

00:36:55.080 --> 00:36:57.030
we just have to look at
what is the equivalent

00:36:57.030 --> 00:37:01.380
effect of a 7% increase
in the price, which

00:37:01.380 --> 00:37:03.672
is exactly what we have here.

00:37:03.672 --> 00:37:05.130
So essentially,
just to summarize--

00:37:05.130 --> 00:37:07.560
and I think the math is, in some
sense, not that interesting.

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:09.030
But essentially,
to summarize, it's

00:37:09.030 --> 00:37:12.510
like the larger our reaction
is to this intervention,

00:37:12.510 --> 00:37:14.490
the more inattentive
most people have

00:37:14.490 --> 00:37:19.410
been before because if they're
inattentive to start with,

00:37:19.410 --> 00:37:22.040
they react more to making
things more salient.

00:37:22.040 --> 00:37:26.180
So let me show you what
this looks like in practice.

00:37:26.180 --> 00:37:28.760
Again, the goal here is to
estimate a change in demand

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:30.710
from making taxes fully salient.

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:33.380
Again, here's the
original tag, and here's

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:35.600
the experimental tag.

00:37:35.600 --> 00:37:38.060
It's very, very salient, very,
very clear, and very hard

00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:38.930
to miss for people.

00:37:38.930 --> 00:37:40.305
And the assumption
essentially is

00:37:40.305 --> 00:37:44.120
that people pay now full
attention to this new tag.

00:37:44.120 --> 00:37:45.920
They have a three-week
period in which--

00:37:45.920 --> 00:37:48.657
and this is an
experiment in California.

00:37:48.657 --> 00:37:50.240
They have a three-week
period in which

00:37:50.240 --> 00:37:53.700
they modify price
tags of certain items

00:37:53.700 --> 00:37:55.700
so that they go essentially
to different stores.

00:37:55.700 --> 00:37:56.690
They pick one store.

00:37:56.690 --> 00:37:59.060
And then essentially,
they modify the price tag

00:37:59.060 --> 00:38:02.090
only of the subset
of randomized goods.

00:38:02.090 --> 00:38:06.950
And they make the after-tax
price salient in addition

00:38:06.950 --> 00:38:08.630
to the pre-tax price, right?

00:38:08.630 --> 00:38:11.390
The pre-tax price is
already very salient here.

00:38:11.390 --> 00:38:16.073
In addition, they make the
after-tax price very salient.

00:38:16.073 --> 00:38:17.490
And now they're
going to do what's

00:38:17.490 --> 00:38:21.360
called a triple-diff estimate,
which is, in some sense, a very

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:24.420
funky or fancy word just to
say what we're going to do

00:38:24.420 --> 00:38:29.280
is we compare the
sales or the demand

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:32.080
during the treatment
periods to the following.

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:33.360
So there's a treatment period.

00:38:33.360 --> 00:38:37.140
We compare how much of certain
goods have been treated.

00:38:37.140 --> 00:38:40.860
How much do the sales change
compared to the previous week

00:38:40.860 --> 00:38:43.002
sales for the same items?

00:38:43.002 --> 00:38:44.460
Second, we're going
to compare them

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:47.940
to sales for items in which
the tax was not made salient.

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:51.720
So there's some goods in the
store for which the tax was not

00:38:51.720 --> 00:38:52.950
made salient.

00:38:52.950 --> 00:38:56.140
And then finally, there's
going to be control stores.

00:38:56.140 --> 00:38:58.050
So we're going to
look at essentially,

00:38:58.050 --> 00:39:00.240
in the stores that
receive the treatment

00:39:00.240 --> 00:39:02.850
or in the store that receives
the treatment, what happens

00:39:02.850 --> 00:39:05.160
to the goods that receive
the treatment compared

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:07.650
to the goods that don't
receive the treatment?

00:39:07.650 --> 00:39:11.940
We compare that to demand
before the treatment was

00:39:11.940 --> 00:39:15.235
enacted for both of
those types of goods.

00:39:15.235 --> 00:39:16.860
Essentially, what's
the relative change

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:20.940
in demand for the treated versus
the non-treated items before

00:39:20.940 --> 00:39:21.555
versus after?

00:39:21.555 --> 00:39:22.930
So that's essentially
what people

00:39:22.930 --> 00:39:26.710
would call a diff in diff,
like difference in differences.

00:39:26.710 --> 00:39:28.980
And in addition to that,
they compare that difference

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:31.770
in differences to the same
difference in differences

00:39:31.770 --> 00:39:32.715
in the control stores.

00:39:32.715 --> 00:39:36.010
So let me show you exactly
what this looks like.

00:39:36.010 --> 00:39:37.410
So this is a bit
of a messy table

00:39:37.410 --> 00:39:39.430
or a table with a
lot of information.

00:39:39.430 --> 00:39:41.380
But it's in fact quite simple.

00:39:41.380 --> 00:39:44.280
So what we have here is at
the top is a treatment store.

00:39:44.280 --> 00:39:46.970
And at the bottom, there's
some control stores.

00:39:46.970 --> 00:39:49.500
So in the control stores,
nothing has been changed.

00:39:49.500 --> 00:39:52.050
So there's no experiment.

00:39:52.050 --> 00:39:54.960
There's no additional tax
and so on being added.

00:39:54.960 --> 00:39:57.645
In the treatment stores, there's
going to be control categories

00:39:57.645 --> 00:39:59.640
and treated categories.

00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:01.890
Notice that they didn't fully
randomize all the goods.

00:40:01.890 --> 00:40:04.140
So it's not like if there's
one brush next to another,

00:40:04.140 --> 00:40:06.420
one brush has taxes versus not.

00:40:06.420 --> 00:40:09.090
Presumably, because they're
trying to minimize spillovers

00:40:09.090 --> 00:40:12.125
in some sense, if you only
make this tax salient for one

00:40:12.125 --> 00:40:13.500
good that's next
to another good,

00:40:13.500 --> 00:40:15.917
people would get very confused
because they're like, well,

00:40:15.917 --> 00:40:18.510
why does this one have
taxes made salient and then

00:40:18.510 --> 00:40:19.590
the other one not?

00:40:19.590 --> 00:40:22.200
So now this is across
categories where people maybe

00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:24.780
only pay attention to certain
goods in certain categories

00:40:24.780 --> 00:40:26.630
to start with.

00:40:26.630 --> 00:40:28.810
So what we're seeing
here is now here,

00:40:28.810 --> 00:40:31.885
these are the control categories
and the treated categories.

00:40:31.885 --> 00:40:34.510
And we can look at what's called
the difference in differences.

00:40:34.510 --> 00:40:37.200
We can look at the change in
demand in the treatment stores.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:38.440
What we're going to
look at is essentially

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:40.540
the change in demand in
the control categories

00:40:40.540 --> 00:40:42.440
and the treatment categories.

00:40:42.440 --> 00:40:46.150
So what we see here
is we can compare

00:40:46.150 --> 00:40:48.670
how much is sold in the
experimental period, which

00:40:48.670 --> 00:40:52.270
is this row here,
compared to our baseline.

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:55.210
What we see is essentially
demand in the control

00:40:55.210 --> 00:40:57.850
categories was going up
a little bit by 0.84.

00:40:57.850 --> 00:40:59.590
That's just because
of seasonalities.

00:40:59.590 --> 00:41:01.840
Maybe people were just
buying more anyway

00:41:01.840 --> 00:41:03.250
for whatever reason.

00:41:03.250 --> 00:41:06.100
And in the treated categories
over the same period,

00:41:06.100 --> 00:41:08.260
comparing essentially
the experimental periods

00:41:08.260 --> 00:41:12.920
to the baseline period,
demand went down.

00:41:12.920 --> 00:41:14.800
So now the difference
in differences estimate

00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:17.620
is essentially the change in
demand in the treatment stores,

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:20.153
comparing the treated categories
compared to the control

00:41:20.153 --> 00:41:21.820
categories, which is
just the difference

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:24.170
between this column
and this column,

00:41:24.170 --> 00:41:27.570
which is minus 2.14 units.

00:41:27.570 --> 00:41:28.300
OK.

00:41:28.300 --> 00:41:31.150
So that's essentially,
how much did the demand

00:41:31.150 --> 00:41:34.750
change before versus after in
the treated categories compared

00:41:34.750 --> 00:41:38.330
to the same change in
the control categories?

00:41:38.330 --> 00:41:41.090
So that's essentially
a difference

00:41:41.090 --> 00:41:43.240
in differences estimator.

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:45.560
Now, they also have
the control stores.

00:41:45.560 --> 00:41:48.110
Why would we want the
control stores, as well?

00:41:48.110 --> 00:41:50.510
Why is that helpful to have?

00:41:50.510 --> 00:41:53.930
Suppose that improved sunscreen,
and now it's getting warmer.

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:57.410
It's really hot, and everybody
was out buying sunscreen.

00:41:57.410 --> 00:41:59.540
Then you see essentially
people's demand

00:41:59.540 --> 00:42:00.645
in the control categories.

00:42:00.645 --> 00:42:02.270
The treatment category
goes up by a lot

00:42:02.270 --> 00:42:04.070
or goes down by a lot
for whatever reason.

00:42:04.070 --> 00:42:07.070
Suppose it's umbrellas, and
one week was really rainy,

00:42:07.070 --> 00:42:08.780
and the other one was not rainy.

00:42:08.780 --> 00:42:12.140
And we see now essentially
seasonal or other differences

00:42:12.140 --> 00:42:15.297
over time in some of the
categories that would,

00:42:15.297 --> 00:42:16.880
even if it's randomized,
it could just

00:42:16.880 --> 00:42:18.480
happen to be the case.

00:42:18.480 --> 00:42:21.230
So that would not have to
do anything with a sales tax

00:42:21.230 --> 00:42:21.890
being salient.

00:42:21.890 --> 00:42:23.508
That's just by chance.

00:42:23.508 --> 00:42:25.550
So now it's very nice to
have some control stores

00:42:25.550 --> 00:42:27.410
where we can look at like the
same difference in difference

00:42:27.410 --> 00:42:30.060
estimates and some of the
control stores, in some sense,

00:42:30.060 --> 00:42:31.193
like a placebo.

00:42:31.193 --> 00:42:32.360
They can do the same things.

00:42:32.360 --> 00:42:34.860
There's going to be the control
categories and the treatment

00:42:34.860 --> 00:42:35.960
categories.

00:42:35.960 --> 00:42:38.150
Notice, to be very clear,
in the control stores,

00:42:38.150 --> 00:42:42.190
the treated categories do not
receive any actual treatment.

00:42:42.190 --> 00:42:44.330
So we can do the same
difference in differences.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:47.900
And what we see here is now
that there's essentially

00:42:47.900 --> 00:42:48.750
no difference here.

00:42:48.750 --> 00:42:51.110
So the demand in the
control categories

00:42:51.110 --> 00:42:54.403
went up a little bit for
whatever reason in the treated.

00:42:54.403 --> 00:42:56.820
And this is a little bit smaller
than in this other store.

00:42:56.820 --> 00:42:58.950
This difference is not
statistically significant.

00:42:58.950 --> 00:43:01.200
But anyway, the control
categories go up a little bit.

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:03.433
The treated categories
go also up a little bit.

00:43:03.433 --> 00:43:05.600
When you do this difference
in differences estimate,

00:43:05.600 --> 00:43:07.453
you find essentially
no difference.

00:43:07.453 --> 00:43:08.870
In the control
categories, there's

00:43:08.870 --> 00:43:11.360
no change in the
treated categories

00:43:11.360 --> 00:43:13.610
compared to the baseline
compared to the control

00:43:13.610 --> 00:43:14.200
categories.

00:43:14.200 --> 00:43:16.820
So difference in difference
estimate in the control

00:43:16.820 --> 00:43:18.722
category is essentially 0.

00:43:18.722 --> 00:43:20.930
And now what you can do is
essentially the difference

00:43:20.930 --> 00:43:22.190
in differences estimate.

00:43:22.190 --> 00:43:22.940
You can compare.

00:43:22.940 --> 00:43:25.130
You can subtract
this number here

00:43:25.130 --> 00:43:27.170
minus this number
here, which gives you

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:31.100
the triple-diff estimate,
which essentially

00:43:31.100 --> 00:43:34.070
is the relative change of
treatment versus control

00:43:34.070 --> 00:43:37.580
before and after and treatment
versus control stores.

00:43:37.580 --> 00:43:41.970
It's a little bit lots of
differences in your head.

00:43:41.970 --> 00:43:45.570
But I hope this comparison
from the table makes it clear.

00:43:45.570 --> 00:43:48.728
Any questions on the
estimate or the procedure

00:43:48.728 --> 00:43:49.520
that they're doing?

00:43:58.750 --> 00:43:59.380
OK.

00:43:59.380 --> 00:44:02.200
So what we see here now
is essentially now making

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:05.290
these taxes salient in
the treated categories

00:44:05.290 --> 00:44:09.010
in the treatment stores
reduces demand, right?

00:44:09.010 --> 00:44:10.670
Because essentially,
demand goes down.

00:44:10.670 --> 00:44:11.860
Why does the demand go down?

00:44:11.860 --> 00:44:16.678
Well, the perceived price that
people face has now gone up.

00:44:16.678 --> 00:44:18.220
And now they buy
less of these goods,

00:44:18.220 --> 00:44:21.280
presumably because before,
they were not paying attention.

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:22.570
Now the price goes up.

00:44:22.570 --> 00:44:25.570
And now, essentially,
demand falls, as it should,

00:44:25.570 --> 00:44:29.650
because now things
are more expensive.

00:44:29.650 --> 00:44:32.690
And this is here the result. The
average quantity sold decreases

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:35.600
by 2.2 units-- this is
units of the goods--

00:44:35.600 --> 00:44:37.610
relative to baseline
level of 25.

00:44:37.610 --> 00:44:41.240
That's an 8.8% decline.

00:44:41.240 --> 00:44:42.965
And now we can use
our own formula

00:44:42.965 --> 00:44:46.700
and compute the
degree of inattention.

00:44:46.700 --> 00:44:54.440
Essentially, now we can say, OK,
now we know what the tax was.

00:44:54.440 --> 00:44:57.850
The tax was 7.375%.

00:44:57.850 --> 00:45:02.390
We can estimate the price
elasticity in some other ways.

00:45:02.390 --> 00:45:05.380
Essentially, we can say,
what happens if prices go up

00:45:05.380 --> 00:45:07.728
by 1% for other reasons?

00:45:07.728 --> 00:45:10.270
What if the salient component
that's already salient goes up?

00:45:10.270 --> 00:45:13.120
This is week-by-week
variation across stores.

00:45:13.120 --> 00:45:16.480
So if the prices go up,
what's the price elasticity?

00:45:16.480 --> 00:45:18.370
And the estimate of
those price elasticity

00:45:18.370 --> 00:45:21.100
is also given from
other variation.

00:45:21.100 --> 00:45:22.660
That's 1.59.

00:45:22.660 --> 00:45:24.598
And now we can essentially
back out theta.

00:45:24.598 --> 00:45:26.140
Essentially, what
we're trying to ask

00:45:26.140 --> 00:45:34.510
is we have a change in 2.2 units
that is making prices salient.

00:45:34.510 --> 00:45:36.880
Now the question is, well,
how large of a change

00:45:36.880 --> 00:45:42.220
is it relative to a change in
prices of 1%, 2%, and so on?

00:45:42.220 --> 00:45:47.440
We know that essentially the
price elasticity is 1.59.

00:45:47.440 --> 00:45:50.780
So we can essentially
just back out theta.

00:45:50.780 --> 00:45:52.360
And so what we get
from this formula

00:45:52.360 --> 00:45:58.150
now is that theta is about 0.75,
which says that consumers react

00:45:58.150 --> 00:46:01.480
to price changes due to sales
tax changes only a quarter as

00:46:01.480 --> 00:46:03.490
much as to other price changes.

00:46:03.490 --> 00:46:08.200
So essentially, consumers are
very inattentive, in fact,

00:46:08.200 --> 00:46:12.080
to sales taxes, to
sales tax changes.

00:46:12.080 --> 00:46:13.840
In fact, they only
perceive a quarter

00:46:13.840 --> 00:46:19.280
as much as any other price
changes in the world.

00:46:19.280 --> 00:46:21.730
And that's really saying,
look, people really

00:46:21.730 --> 00:46:23.980
seem to be missing these
things that are not salient.

00:46:23.980 --> 00:46:27.080
Now if you make them salient,
people change their behavior.

00:46:27.080 --> 00:46:31.000
Therefore, they must have been
inattentive to start with.

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:33.805
In addition to that
kind of evidence,

00:46:33.805 --> 00:46:35.500
Chetty et al. also
have some evidence

00:46:35.500 --> 00:46:38.770
on using non-experimental
variation.

00:46:38.770 --> 00:46:40.810
And in some sense, you
could say the evidence

00:46:40.810 --> 00:46:43.602
that I just showed you from
the store is a little bit

00:46:43.602 --> 00:46:46.060
weird because, in some sense,
you see these different tags.

00:46:46.060 --> 00:46:48.640
And maybe the tags
raise attention

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:50.740
to the price even
regardless of the tax.

00:46:50.740 --> 00:46:53.150
And it's a little bit
weird in some ways.

00:46:53.150 --> 00:46:55.720
So it's quite nice to have
some complementary evidence

00:46:55.720 --> 00:47:03.140
of a non-experimental
panel deliberation.

00:47:03.140 --> 00:47:07.810
And so what they do is they
look at beer consumption.

00:47:07.810 --> 00:47:12.640
And it turns out beer, tobacco,
and other types of goods

00:47:12.640 --> 00:47:16.600
have two types of
taxes levied on them.

00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:20.020
They have an excise tax, which
is included in the price.

00:47:20.020 --> 00:47:23.773
This is highly salient
during choice the process

00:47:23.773 --> 00:47:25.690
because essentially it's
in the price already.

00:47:25.690 --> 00:47:27.997
So if taxes go up,
essentially, the price goes up.

00:47:27.997 --> 00:47:29.830
And people will notice
if they pay attention

00:47:29.830 --> 00:47:32.170
or since they pay attention
to prices, since they

00:47:32.170 --> 00:47:36.280
like the price tag already.

00:47:36.280 --> 00:47:37.660
And then there's a sales tax.

00:47:37.660 --> 00:47:39.970
This is the tax that we were
just talking about before.

00:47:39.970 --> 00:47:42.460
That's essentially very opaque
during the choice process,

00:47:42.460 --> 00:47:43.810
as we just showed.

00:47:43.810 --> 00:47:46.570
And now we can look at
variation across states

00:47:46.570 --> 00:47:52.300
and over time of changes in
excise taxes and sales taxes.

00:47:52.300 --> 00:47:54.280
And we can look at,
how much do people

00:47:54.280 --> 00:47:57.700
react to excise taxes
relative to how much people

00:47:57.700 --> 00:47:59.440
react to sales taxes.

00:47:59.440 --> 00:48:01.450
And that relative reaction
will tell us, again,

00:48:01.450 --> 00:48:04.030
something about theta.

00:48:04.030 --> 00:48:07.210
And what Chetty et al. finds
in here is a table for that.

00:48:07.210 --> 00:48:10.690
Essentially, when you look
at changes in excise taxes,

00:48:10.690 --> 00:48:13.210
this tax is very salient.

00:48:13.210 --> 00:48:18.850
The price elasticity
is above 0.8 or 0.9.

00:48:18.850 --> 00:48:22.600
So essentially, when
the price goes up by 1%,

00:48:22.600 --> 00:48:26.680
people react by about almost 1%.

00:48:26.680 --> 00:48:30.400
In contrast, there's some
differences in estimates.

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:32.590
But once you control
for things properly,

00:48:32.590 --> 00:48:35.560
people essentially do not
react to the sales tax at all.

00:48:35.560 --> 00:48:39.520
Maybe a little bit, but overall,
the number's very, very low.

00:48:39.520 --> 00:48:42.180
And now, essentially, the ratio
of these types of reaction

00:48:42.180 --> 00:48:45.160
tells you how
attentive people are.

00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:47.900
Essentially, if you
divide, say, for example--

00:48:47.900 --> 00:48:53.427
if you took column number three,
if you divide 0.003 by 0.86,

00:48:53.427 --> 00:48:55.510
and you have to do a little
bit of additional math

00:48:55.510 --> 00:48:57.550
that's uninteresting--
you essentially

00:48:57.550 --> 00:49:00.430
will get a result that,
essentially, people do not

00:49:00.430 --> 00:49:03.610
pay attention to sales taxes.

00:49:03.610 --> 00:49:06.490
1 minus theta is
eventually close to 0.

00:49:06.490 --> 00:49:09.400
Put differently, the degree
of inattention is almost 1.

00:49:09.400 --> 00:49:11.170
Theta is almost 1.

00:49:11.170 --> 00:49:14.620
So essentially, people
do not pay attention

00:49:14.620 --> 00:49:18.190
to these types of taxes.

00:49:18.190 --> 00:49:20.740
Inattention is almost complete.

00:49:20.740 --> 00:49:23.560
So there's substantial
consumer inattention

00:49:23.560 --> 00:49:26.300
to non-transparent taxes.

00:49:26.300 --> 00:49:29.760
So what I've shown you
so far is, essentially,

00:49:29.760 --> 00:49:31.300
the existence of inattention.

00:49:31.300 --> 00:49:33.550
It doesn't say why
people are inattentive.

00:49:33.550 --> 00:49:37.040
It could be people just can't
do the math in their head.

00:49:37.040 --> 00:49:39.040
It could be people don't
want to bother with it.

00:49:39.040 --> 00:49:41.457
They're sort of saying, well,
it's kind of a small change.

00:49:41.457 --> 00:49:42.520
So why do we really care?

00:49:42.520 --> 00:49:45.607
It could be that people who
buy alcohol half of the time

00:49:45.607 --> 00:49:47.440
are drunk, and they
don't pay any attention.

00:49:47.440 --> 00:49:54.020
There's no modeling in any way
of, why are people doing this?

00:49:54.020 --> 00:49:57.580
This is just saying this shows
the existence of inattention

00:49:57.580 --> 00:50:00.070
in those kinds of
consumer choices.

00:50:00.070 --> 00:50:02.020
It doesn't say why
people are inattentive.

00:50:02.020 --> 00:50:04.120
And you might say,
well, 7% of a tax

00:50:04.120 --> 00:50:05.770
is kind of a small distortion.

00:50:05.770 --> 00:50:10.460
So it might be actually
optimal to miss that,

00:50:10.460 --> 00:50:12.712
which is a reasonable approach.

00:50:12.712 --> 00:50:14.170
It is probably
quite a bit of money

00:50:14.170 --> 00:50:15.920
and quite a bit of
distortion if you think

00:50:15.920 --> 00:50:17.740
about it and you actually--

00:50:17.740 --> 00:50:19.210
7% is not nothing.

00:50:19.210 --> 00:50:21.363
But if you have a
lot of money anyway,

00:50:21.363 --> 00:50:23.780
you might as well just not pay
any attention to that stuff

00:50:23.780 --> 00:50:27.700
and if that helps you pay
attention to other things.

00:50:27.700 --> 00:50:30.100
Notice that even
then, that shows

00:50:30.100 --> 00:50:31.960
the existence of inattention.

00:50:31.960 --> 00:50:33.460
It's just a bit of
a question, like,

00:50:33.460 --> 00:50:34.900
how important is inattention?

00:50:34.900 --> 00:50:37.500
And this actually gets
me to the next point,

00:50:37.500 --> 00:50:39.250
which is a question
of, why should we care

00:50:39.250 --> 00:50:40.810
about inattention to taxes?

00:50:40.810 --> 00:50:44.120
Why is that important or
interesting potentially?

00:50:44.120 --> 00:50:46.205
Question exactly is,
who's paying attention?

00:50:46.205 --> 00:50:47.330
Who's not paying attention?

00:50:47.330 --> 00:50:49.010
And then who's
sort of distorting

00:50:49.010 --> 00:50:50.280
their behavior potentially?

00:50:50.280 --> 00:50:53.600
There's lots of interesting
issues about heterogeneity

00:50:53.600 --> 00:50:56.150
and who's paying attention.

00:50:56.150 --> 00:50:58.610
Let me talk about
this in a second.

00:50:58.610 --> 00:51:00.680
Let me ask differently.

00:51:00.680 --> 00:51:04.070
Why is it that some taxes, the
excise taxes, are very salient?

00:51:04.070 --> 00:51:06.860
And why is it that other
taxes are not salient?

00:51:06.860 --> 00:51:08.820
What do you think about that?

00:51:08.820 --> 00:51:09.680
Is that an accident?

00:51:09.680 --> 00:51:12.140
Or why is it that the taxes
for alcohol and tobacco,

00:51:12.140 --> 00:51:13.910
et cetera, are very salient?

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:16.370
And why is it that other
taxes for shampoo or

00:51:16.370 --> 00:51:19.580
whatever are
actually not salient?

00:51:19.580 --> 00:51:23.055
There's two simple objectives
if you took a public economics

00:51:23.055 --> 00:51:24.890
class, if you took
John Gruber's class,

00:51:24.890 --> 00:51:28.070
but also if you
took 1401 or 1403.

00:51:28.070 --> 00:51:31.910
The reason why the
government levies taxes is--

00:51:31.910 --> 00:51:33.830
one big reason is to
generate revenue, right?

00:51:33.830 --> 00:51:34.955
The government needs money.

00:51:34.955 --> 00:51:36.690
Somehow, we need to tax people.

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:39.770
And the issue, of course,
is that if you levy taxes

00:51:39.770 --> 00:51:42.470
on some goods
versus others, that

00:51:42.470 --> 00:51:44.600
can distort consumer choices.

00:51:44.600 --> 00:51:47.960
And there's essentially
some theorems

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:54.260
and some considerations about
which goods should you tax.

00:51:54.260 --> 00:51:56.480
And ideally, you would
tax goods that people

00:51:56.480 --> 00:51:58.490
are consuming anyway.

00:51:58.490 --> 00:52:00.410
Essentially, what you
want is people make--

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:02.810
so essentially, when you
have taxes on some goods

00:52:02.810 --> 00:52:05.450
but not on others, if
people have different price

00:52:05.450 --> 00:52:07.490
elasticities on some
goods versus others

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:11.840
and if you increase one good or
all goods by a certain amount,

00:52:11.840 --> 00:52:14.660
if people have different
price elasticities,

00:52:14.660 --> 00:52:17.290
then you might distort
their behavior.

00:52:17.290 --> 00:52:20.440
So if you increase and you
start taxing one thing and not

00:52:20.440 --> 00:52:23.600
another, people might
shift to the other good.

00:52:23.600 --> 00:52:26.690
And we don't want that because,
presumably, people are already

00:52:26.690 --> 00:52:29.090
optimizing to start with.

00:52:29.090 --> 00:52:31.370
Now, if people are
inelastic to certain goods,

00:52:31.370 --> 00:52:33.620
if people need
certain goods anyway

00:52:33.620 --> 00:52:34.970
and they buy them anyway--

00:52:34.970 --> 00:52:37.220
and the last thing, essentially,
there's public goods.

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:41.000
Public economics would tell you
or some theories would tell you

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:44.030
you should tax these goods more.

00:52:44.030 --> 00:52:47.450
Now, distortion, when people
are-- so the distortions

00:52:47.450 --> 00:52:50.810
are lower if people don't
fully react to taxes.

00:52:50.810 --> 00:52:54.030
That could be if, for example,
you started taxing bread,

00:52:54.030 --> 00:52:57.890
for example, while everybody--
or certain goods like potatoes,

00:52:57.890 --> 00:53:00.470
where everybody needs to
buy these goods anyway

00:53:00.470 --> 00:53:02.360
because people need to eat--

00:53:02.360 --> 00:53:06.620
well, then, there
would be very low--

00:53:09.140 --> 00:53:12.430
these goods would
be very inelastic.

00:53:12.430 --> 00:53:14.180
And that's because
they need those things.

00:53:14.180 --> 00:53:15.740
Not because they're
inattentive, but just

00:53:15.740 --> 00:53:17.365
because they need
these types of goods.

00:53:17.365 --> 00:53:21.830
Now, there's obviously
issues with poverty.

00:53:21.830 --> 00:53:24.320
We don't want to tax
the poor too much.

00:53:24.320 --> 00:53:27.630
But in general, they want to
tax things that are inelastic.

00:53:27.630 --> 00:53:30.940
And so in a way, if people
are inattentive to the taxes,

00:53:30.940 --> 00:53:32.690
in a way, that's great
because now they're

00:53:32.690 --> 00:53:33.970
not distorting their behavior.

00:53:33.970 --> 00:53:36.360
And we can still
get money from them.

00:53:36.360 --> 00:53:40.400
So in some sense, actually,
some of the inattention

00:53:40.400 --> 00:53:42.380
for that purpose
might be actually good

00:53:42.380 --> 00:53:45.620
because now people are not
distorting their behavior

00:53:45.620 --> 00:53:49.310
by looking at those prices.

00:53:49.310 --> 00:53:51.620
So being inattentive
in some ways is good.

00:53:51.620 --> 00:53:54.720
But exactly as Maya was
saying, for some goods--

00:53:54.720 --> 00:53:58.580
and these are often labeled
as sin goods or the like,

00:53:58.580 --> 00:54:01.500
where there's either
externalities or internalities.

00:54:01.500 --> 00:54:04.820
For example, if you think
about tobacco or alcohol,

00:54:04.820 --> 00:54:05.870
there are externalities.

00:54:05.870 --> 00:54:09.590
Tobacco, for example, secondhand
smoking is bad for others.

00:54:09.590 --> 00:54:11.750
For alcohol, there's
often externalities

00:54:11.750 --> 00:54:15.390
in terms of drunk driving
or violence or the like.

00:54:15.390 --> 00:54:18.350
So the government wants to
increase the price of alcohol

00:54:18.350 --> 00:54:22.430
because when people are making
choices of how much alcohol

00:54:22.430 --> 00:54:25.190
to buy, they might not take into
account the effects of alcohol

00:54:25.190 --> 00:54:26.420
on others.

00:54:26.420 --> 00:54:29.570
By internalities, I mean
people might not necessarily

00:54:29.570 --> 00:54:33.620
take into account the
effect of alcohol or tobacco

00:54:33.620 --> 00:54:34.858
on themselves.

00:54:34.858 --> 00:54:36.400
This is what we
discussed previously.

00:54:36.400 --> 00:54:38.240
This could be because
of present bias.

00:54:38.240 --> 00:54:41.900
This could be because of
biased beliefs or the like.

00:54:41.900 --> 00:54:44.552
Essentially, people might
hurt their future selves.

00:54:44.552 --> 00:54:46.010
And the government
might say, well,

00:54:46.010 --> 00:54:49.070
let's increase taxes
because their future sales--

00:54:49.070 --> 00:54:50.510
people might like
that there might

00:54:50.510 --> 00:54:52.940
be a way of helping
people, for instance,

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:55.080
deal with self control problems.

00:54:55.080 --> 00:54:57.980
So here, the
government explicitly

00:54:57.980 --> 00:55:01.370
wants consumers to
react to the taxes.

00:55:01.370 --> 00:55:03.188
The point is not to
make money from people.

00:55:03.188 --> 00:55:04.730
And in fact, sometimes
you're worried

00:55:04.730 --> 00:55:07.200
about making too much
money from people.

00:55:07.200 --> 00:55:10.040
The point here is really
to change behavior

00:55:10.040 --> 00:55:13.790
to reduce the behaviors
that are being taxed.

00:55:13.790 --> 00:55:16.650
So you want to make such
taxes particularly salient.

00:55:16.650 --> 00:55:17.150
Ready?

00:55:17.150 --> 00:55:22.070
Now, look at the taxes on
alcohol versus the taxes on--

00:55:22.070 --> 00:55:24.460
some of the excise taxes
versus the sales taxes.

00:55:24.460 --> 00:55:27.710
The excise taxes are
precisely salient because we

00:55:27.710 --> 00:55:31.828
want people to react to it
while the sales taxes are not.

00:55:31.828 --> 00:55:33.620
Of course, there's
variation across places.

00:55:33.620 --> 00:55:36.320
But it's not an accident that
we see this in the world the way

00:55:36.320 --> 00:55:37.310
that is.

00:55:37.310 --> 00:55:39.980
Now, one thing that's
quite interesting now is--

00:55:39.980 --> 00:55:43.070
and I think Jos or
[INAUDIBLE] was saying that.

00:55:43.070 --> 00:55:45.660
It's like when consumers
are heterogeneous,

00:55:45.660 --> 00:55:47.850
then there's a lot of
quite interesting issues.

00:55:47.850 --> 00:55:50.850
For example, if you have
the poor paying more or less

00:55:50.850 --> 00:55:53.700
attention compared to the rich
or if only a subset of people

00:55:53.700 --> 00:55:56.970
pay attention to those
goods, then in a way,

00:55:56.970 --> 00:56:00.090
you would find that the average
elasticity is still quite low.

00:56:00.090 --> 00:56:02.400
But some people are actually
distorting their behavior

00:56:02.400 --> 00:56:04.860
quite a bit, and others do not.

00:56:04.860 --> 00:56:11.010
And that gets relatively
quickly quite complicated.

00:56:11.010 --> 00:56:13.063
And you could then
get into situations

00:56:13.063 --> 00:56:15.480
where you make some people a
lot worse off and some people

00:56:15.480 --> 00:56:20.150
better off when making
something salient versus not.

00:56:20.150 --> 00:56:21.360
Any questions on all of this?

00:56:28.460 --> 00:56:29.360
OK.

00:56:29.360 --> 00:56:32.058
So then we get to
the next question.

00:56:32.058 --> 00:56:34.100
This is getting a little
bit at the question that

00:56:34.100 --> 00:56:37.340
was asked previously about,
can inattention or attention

00:56:37.340 --> 00:56:39.200
have large effects?

00:56:39.200 --> 00:56:44.300
And so on the one hand,
you might say, well,

00:56:44.300 --> 00:56:46.550
people's choices-- for
example, consumption patterns--

00:56:46.550 --> 00:56:49.280
are distorted due to
limited attention.

00:56:49.280 --> 00:56:53.510
But you might ask, well,
if it's really true

00:56:53.510 --> 00:56:56.090
that people's consumption
patterns have really distorted

00:56:56.090 --> 00:56:59.330
that much, if I'm so much worse
off by not paying attention

00:56:59.330 --> 00:57:01.910
to things, well, eventually,
I'm going to notice this.

00:57:01.910 --> 00:57:03.800
Somebody is going to tell me.

00:57:03.800 --> 00:57:09.320
Or in a way, I notice
myself eventually

00:57:09.320 --> 00:57:11.810
that I'm doing things really
worse compared to my friends.

00:57:11.810 --> 00:57:16.460
And eventually, if things
are really distorted a lot,

00:57:16.460 --> 00:57:19.290
I might pay attention to it.

00:57:19.290 --> 00:57:23.540
So the underlying idea is
that, potentially, people

00:57:23.540 --> 00:57:26.660
are actually inattentive
in the sense of saying,

00:57:26.660 --> 00:57:29.630
look, people's attention
is limited in some ways.

00:57:29.630 --> 00:57:35.060
But it's optimal for
people to pay attention

00:57:35.060 --> 00:57:36.770
to things that are
really important.

00:57:36.770 --> 00:57:38.187
And there, the
underlying question

00:57:38.187 --> 00:57:39.560
is, what is salient to people?

00:57:39.560 --> 00:57:41.887
And how do people
decide what to focus on?

00:57:41.887 --> 00:57:43.970
And won't people pay
attention to important things

00:57:43.970 --> 00:57:47.473
anyway if they have to?

00:57:47.473 --> 00:57:48.890
And so then the
question is, well,

00:57:48.890 --> 00:57:50.750
how is it possible
that inattention could

00:57:50.750 --> 00:57:52.780
have large effects anyway?

00:57:52.780 --> 00:57:55.790
And so the next paper is
a good example of that.

00:57:55.790 --> 00:57:58.820
And here's a very intuitive
example of why that might be.

00:57:58.820 --> 00:58:00.570
So consider the
following situation.

00:58:00.570 --> 00:58:02.960
You have been getting headaches.

00:58:02.960 --> 00:58:04.550
You go to the doctor.

00:58:04.550 --> 00:58:07.010
And the doctor asks you
whether it gets worse

00:58:07.010 --> 00:58:08.900
after eating certain foods.

00:58:08.900 --> 00:58:10.860
And so what are
you going to say?

00:58:10.860 --> 00:58:15.590
Well, the answer will probably
be like, I don't know.

00:58:15.590 --> 00:58:17.060
And why is that?

00:58:17.060 --> 00:58:21.481
Why might you just not even know
the answer to that question?

00:58:21.481 --> 00:58:24.310
An underlying
theory in your mind

00:58:24.310 --> 00:58:26.500
of why you might be
getting headaches.

00:58:26.500 --> 00:58:29.350
And you might just
not have a theory

00:58:29.350 --> 00:58:31.340
that it's related to
your food consumption.

00:58:31.340 --> 00:58:33.950
So while you have lots
of data in front of you--

00:58:33.950 --> 00:58:36.160
you eat every day, you
get headaches on some days

00:58:36.160 --> 00:58:37.900
and not on others-- you could
surely pay attention to it

00:58:37.900 --> 00:58:38.860
if you wanted to.

00:58:38.860 --> 00:58:41.230
But it's not even a
theory in your mind,

00:58:41.230 --> 00:58:44.570
so you won't even encode
the relevant information

00:58:44.570 --> 00:58:47.270
if you don't expect to have
food allergies or gluten

00:58:47.270 --> 00:58:48.940
allergy or the like
if you don't expect

00:58:48.940 --> 00:58:50.023
that to be a likely cause.

00:58:50.023 --> 00:58:52.107
Then you're never going
to actually pay attention,

00:58:52.107 --> 00:58:54.850
and you get infinite amounts of
data on every day and headaches

00:58:54.850 --> 00:58:55.990
and food consumption.

00:58:55.990 --> 00:58:58.390
But you're never going
to notice because you

00:58:58.390 --> 00:59:02.312
don't have a theory in your mind
that that might be the case.

00:59:02.312 --> 00:59:04.770
And so there's a relationship
between attention and memory.

00:59:04.770 --> 00:59:07.768
You only remember or pay
attention to stuff that

00:59:07.768 --> 00:59:09.060
actually are theories of yours.

00:59:09.060 --> 00:59:10.602
And then you'll
remember those things

00:59:10.602 --> 00:59:13.160
that you actually paid
attention to in the first place.

00:59:13.160 --> 00:59:15.355
And so selective
attention, then,

00:59:15.355 --> 00:59:17.230
may have persistent
effects on what we learn.

00:59:17.230 --> 00:59:19.570
Essentially, you could
have unlimited amounts

00:59:19.570 --> 00:59:21.160
of information in front of you.

00:59:21.160 --> 00:59:23.410
And you will never
learn because you never

00:59:23.410 --> 00:59:26.170
just had it on your radar that
this information is actually

00:59:26.170 --> 00:59:27.907
relevant for the issue at hand.

00:59:27.907 --> 00:59:29.740
And Josh Schwartzstein
has a very nice model

00:59:29.740 --> 00:59:31.960
that illustrates that.

00:59:31.960 --> 00:59:35.980
Another example
is from medicine.

00:59:35.980 --> 00:59:38.170
Many women died
from childbed fever

00:59:38.170 --> 00:59:40.360
at hospitals in the
mid-19th century.

00:59:40.360 --> 00:59:42.490
The popular theories
were bad smells

00:59:42.490 --> 00:59:45.540
at the hospital, presence
of male doctors wounded

00:59:45.540 --> 00:59:47.020
the modesty of the mothers.

00:59:47.020 --> 00:59:50.290
That's, of course, nonsense.

00:59:50.290 --> 00:59:51.880
The true explanation is germs.

00:59:51.880 --> 00:59:53.830
Doctors didn't wash their hands.

00:59:53.830 --> 00:59:56.110
And again, it's something--
that's not a tricky thing

00:59:56.110 --> 00:59:58.000
to figure out if you
have the idea, if you

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:01.377
have the hypothesis or the idea
that this could be important.

01:00:01.377 --> 01:00:03.835
And presumably, some doctors
are washing their hands anyway

01:00:03.835 --> 01:00:06.760
and sometimes are not, and they
would have a lot fewer deaths.

01:00:06.760 --> 01:00:09.040
But nobody was noticing
because, again, just nobody

01:00:09.040 --> 01:00:10.370
was paying attention.

01:00:10.370 --> 01:00:14.050
So once you have the
right theory in mind,

01:00:14.050 --> 01:00:14.930
then you can test it.

01:00:14.930 --> 01:00:17.305
And then, of course, you can
gather the right information

01:00:17.305 --> 01:00:20.890
and pay attention to the
right information and learn.

01:00:20.890 --> 01:00:25.630
Now, the basic model from
Josh Schwartzstein-- beliefs

01:00:25.630 --> 01:00:28.060
today matter for what
is being attended

01:00:28.060 --> 01:00:31.270
to today, which then affect
people's beliefs tomorrow.

01:00:31.270 --> 01:00:35.890
And now if you don't
attend to the right things,

01:00:35.890 --> 01:00:38.470
if your model of the
world is the wrong model,

01:00:38.470 --> 01:00:41.950
you might never learn to
attend to important aspects

01:00:41.950 --> 01:00:43.070
of the world.

01:00:43.070 --> 01:00:44.980
And so then
forecasts and beliefs

01:00:44.980 --> 01:00:48.490
may be biased and persistently
biased in a systematic fashion.

01:00:48.490 --> 01:00:51.430
And you might persistently
misreact and misattribute

01:00:51.430 --> 01:00:55.170
causes to unimportant variables
because you have never

01:00:55.170 --> 01:00:59.927
even considered the idea of
the correct model of the world.

01:00:59.927 --> 01:01:01.510
And so now the paper
I'm going to show

01:01:01.510 --> 01:01:03.500
you is an example of that.

01:01:03.500 --> 01:01:05.750
This is seaweed
farming in Indonesia,

01:01:05.750 --> 01:01:08.050
which is not immediately
obvious why that's related.

01:01:08.050 --> 01:01:09.500
But I'll show you in a second.

01:01:09.500 --> 01:01:12.496
So this is what seaweed
farming looks like.

01:01:12.496 --> 01:01:14.360
I'll give you this
relatively briefly.

01:01:14.360 --> 01:01:16.660
But essentially, it's
like, at some beaches,

01:01:16.660 --> 01:01:19.750
you can grow seaweeds
in these rows.

01:01:19.750 --> 01:01:21.830
And you see these
round things here,

01:01:21.830 --> 01:01:23.350
which are essentially pods.

01:01:23.350 --> 01:01:25.780
And so there are
many factors that are

01:01:25.780 --> 01:01:27.820
important in seaweed farming.

01:01:27.820 --> 01:01:30.340
Essentially, it's like these
pods, which are essentially

01:01:30.340 --> 01:01:31.900
these round things
that you see here,

01:01:31.900 --> 01:01:34.750
they're essentially
grown in different lines.

01:01:34.750 --> 01:01:36.580
And so if you're
seaweed farmers,

01:01:36.580 --> 01:01:39.160
what's really important
is line spacing--

01:01:39.160 --> 01:01:42.520
or potentially important is line
spacing, pod spacing, and pod

01:01:42.520 --> 01:01:44.560
size, how we got these pods.

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:47.230
Now, how does seaweed
farming actually work?

01:01:47.230 --> 01:01:49.030
I've never done
seaweed farming myself,

01:01:49.030 --> 01:01:50.930
but apparently this
is how it works.

01:01:50.930 --> 01:01:53.470
So farmers use what's called
the bottom method, which

01:01:53.470 --> 01:01:57.490
is they drive wooden stakes
in shallow bottom near shore,

01:01:57.490 --> 01:01:59.560
and they attach lines
to these stakes.

01:01:59.560 --> 01:02:02.290
And they take raw seaweed
from the last harvest

01:02:02.290 --> 01:02:05.350
and cut it into pods, like
these kind of roundish things.

01:02:05.350 --> 01:02:07.480
And the pods are planted
by attaching them

01:02:07.480 --> 01:02:09.850
at a given interval on
the line from the sea.

01:02:09.850 --> 01:02:14.650
And at low tides,
farmers tend the plots.

01:02:14.650 --> 01:02:19.280
And so the seaweed is then
harvested after 30 to 40 days.

01:02:19.280 --> 01:02:22.150
And so now many dimensions
could matter-- the pod size,

01:02:22.150 --> 01:02:24.670
the distance between the lines,
the distance between pods,

01:02:24.670 --> 01:02:25.990
timing, and so on.

01:02:25.990 --> 01:02:28.600
One nice thing about seaweed
is there's many different pods.

01:02:28.600 --> 01:02:30.610
You can actually try
and learn and estimate

01:02:30.610 --> 01:02:33.190
the importance of
these factors over time

01:02:33.190 --> 01:02:35.380
if only you paid attention.

01:02:35.380 --> 01:02:39.910
But the question is, which of
these factors are important?

01:02:39.910 --> 01:02:43.210
And are people paying
attention to those factors?

01:02:46.945 --> 01:02:48.570
And so what the
experiment now is doing

01:02:48.570 --> 01:02:50.638
is there's lots of farmers
in the experiment that

01:02:50.638 --> 01:02:51.555
are quite experienced.

01:02:51.555 --> 01:02:55.320
They have been doing this for a
long time, 18 years of farming.

01:02:55.320 --> 01:02:57.930
Many of them or the vast
majority are literate.

01:02:57.930 --> 01:02:59.820
So these are people
who should really

01:02:59.820 --> 01:03:03.910
know what they're doing in their
seaweed farming experience.

01:03:03.910 --> 01:03:06.840
And so the enumerators
went to visit these farmers

01:03:06.840 --> 01:03:09.480
and to measure and document
their farming methods.

01:03:09.480 --> 01:03:11.960
And when you asked them
about current pod size,

01:03:11.960 --> 01:03:13.950
you just ask them how
big are your pods,

01:03:13.950 --> 01:03:16.932
people just don't
know the answer to.

01:03:16.932 --> 01:03:18.390
They also don't
know the answer to,

01:03:18.390 --> 01:03:19.557
what's the optimum pod size?

01:03:19.557 --> 01:03:21.765
When you just ask them how
big are your pods when you

01:03:21.765 --> 01:03:23.070
plant them, they don't know.

01:03:23.070 --> 01:03:25.028
When you ask them what's
the best way to do it,

01:03:25.028 --> 01:03:25.890
they don't know.

01:03:25.890 --> 01:03:29.012
Importantly, they know exactly
the answer to other questions.

01:03:29.012 --> 01:03:30.720
They know the length
of the typical line.

01:03:30.720 --> 01:03:32.428
They know the distance
between the lines.

01:03:32.428 --> 01:03:34.110
And they also have
very clear ideas

01:03:34.110 --> 01:03:36.210
of what's optimal to do so.

01:03:36.210 --> 01:03:39.300
But they seem to essentially
neglect the pod size dimension

01:03:39.300 --> 01:03:42.770
entirely when they're
thinking about what to do.

01:03:42.770 --> 01:03:45.940
And so in the
experimental trial now,

01:03:45.940 --> 01:03:47.920
they did essentially
different treatments.

01:03:47.920 --> 01:03:49.600
And the treatments
were essentially such

01:03:49.600 --> 01:03:53.350
that farmers were provided
experimental variation

01:03:53.350 --> 01:03:58.030
in the different pod sizes
and essentially induced

01:03:58.030 --> 01:04:00.970
to experiment with pod sizes.

01:04:00.970 --> 01:04:04.645
And in some cases, farmers
were just left on their own.

01:04:04.645 --> 01:04:06.520
They were just induced
to do this experiment.

01:04:06.520 --> 01:04:09.250
And the question was
like, now will farmers

01:04:09.250 --> 01:04:11.540
learn from their own
in this experiment?

01:04:11.540 --> 01:04:14.440
And then in addition, they also
have an information condition

01:04:14.440 --> 01:04:17.620
where they then summarized
that information to the farmers

01:04:17.620 --> 01:04:18.910
in addition.

01:04:18.910 --> 01:04:23.530
So the question is
now, once farmers

01:04:23.530 --> 01:04:25.300
are induced to
experiment, you surely

01:04:25.300 --> 01:04:27.040
would think that
farmers would learn now

01:04:27.040 --> 01:04:29.415
that they're given all the
information that they need on,

01:04:29.415 --> 01:04:31.080
like, here's the
different pod sizes.

01:04:31.080 --> 01:04:32.622
Here's the different
profits that you

01:04:32.622 --> 01:04:36.490
get from the different
types of pods.

01:04:36.490 --> 01:04:39.140
Now they might
learn on their own.

01:04:39.140 --> 01:04:41.770
But if you don't attend to
pod size in the first place,

01:04:41.770 --> 01:04:44.020
if you think it's
irrelevant anyway,

01:04:44.020 --> 01:04:46.390
even if you are induced
to do the experiment,

01:04:46.390 --> 01:04:49.430
you're not going
to learn at all.

01:04:49.430 --> 01:04:52.600
And so then they did essentially
these follow-up surveys.

01:04:52.600 --> 01:04:54.190
And then we'll just skip.

01:04:54.190 --> 01:04:56.830
So now what they do is they
also go through an information

01:04:56.830 --> 01:05:01.358
provision where they essentially
tell farmers the [INAUDIBLE]

01:05:01.358 --> 01:05:02.650
they were doing with everybody.

01:05:02.650 --> 01:05:04.870
But in addition, they
also provided information

01:05:04.870 --> 01:05:07.690
and did some simple
calculations on which

01:05:07.690 --> 01:05:12.300
is the best combination
of pod size and distance.

01:05:12.300 --> 01:05:13.675
Notice that farmers
are literate.

01:05:13.675 --> 01:05:15.410
They're able to do
this on their own.

01:05:15.410 --> 01:05:18.100
But the experiment was just
providing this information

01:05:18.100 --> 01:05:20.590
to farmers explicitly
with a recommendation

01:05:20.590 --> 01:05:24.940
about what's the pod weight and
what is the optimal distance.

01:05:24.940 --> 01:05:26.440
And so now what the
experiment finds

01:05:26.440 --> 01:05:32.140
is large gains from changing
the farming methodology.

01:05:32.140 --> 01:05:34.630
And the trial
participation itself only

01:05:34.630 --> 01:05:36.370
has an insignificant effect.

01:05:36.370 --> 01:05:38.140
That's to say, in
addition, then,

01:05:38.140 --> 01:05:41.470
summarized data for people
has much larger effect.

01:05:41.470 --> 01:05:45.520
Essentially, focusing
people's attention to things

01:05:45.520 --> 01:05:49.480
that they should already know
changes their farming behavior

01:05:49.480 --> 01:05:50.530
a lot.

01:05:50.530 --> 01:05:54.670
And it's essentially
evidence that people were not

01:05:54.670 --> 01:05:56.570
paying attention
in the first place

01:05:56.570 --> 01:05:58.597
even if you make them
participate in a trial

01:05:58.597 --> 01:06:00.430
where they should have
really or could have,

01:06:00.430 --> 01:06:04.940
at least, learned
things on their own.

01:06:04.940 --> 01:06:06.820
There's large
impacts of the trial

01:06:06.820 --> 01:06:09.520
if the data from the trials
is presented to farmers.

01:06:09.520 --> 01:06:11.740
There's no impact of
the trial on dimensions

01:06:11.740 --> 01:06:13.720
that farmers had already
noticed previously,

01:06:13.720 --> 01:06:16.570
presumably because they're
already paying attention

01:06:16.570 --> 01:06:18.642
and were optimizing.

01:06:18.642 --> 01:06:20.100
So now what did we
learn from this?

01:06:20.100 --> 01:06:23.200
And let me quickly
summarize and let you go.

01:06:23.200 --> 01:06:25.110
So we have systematic
learning failures

01:06:25.110 --> 01:06:27.480
even though all the
information was available.

01:06:27.480 --> 01:06:29.430
So farmers simply
did not pay attention

01:06:29.430 --> 01:06:31.380
because they didn't
think that pod size was

01:06:31.380 --> 01:06:34.650
relevant in any
way in their lives.

01:06:34.650 --> 01:06:36.300
And that's a
potential explanation

01:06:36.300 --> 01:06:37.830
why people might
not pay attention

01:06:37.830 --> 01:06:40.560
even to important information
because if your model

01:06:40.560 --> 01:06:43.170
of the world is just
wrong, why would

01:06:43.170 --> 01:06:45.300
you even think that
this is important?

01:06:45.300 --> 01:06:47.880
And the problem here is then
there's never an opportunity

01:06:47.880 --> 01:06:48.690
to actually learn.

01:06:48.690 --> 01:06:50.160
You never even
collect information

01:06:50.160 --> 01:06:51.952
that might reject your
model because you're

01:06:51.952 --> 01:06:55.240
convinced that your model
is right in the first place.

01:06:55.240 --> 01:06:58.290
And so then lack of attention
might generate arbitrarily

01:06:58.290 --> 01:06:59.430
large welfare losses.

01:06:59.430 --> 01:07:02.490
You can really screw up
big time for a long time

01:07:02.490 --> 01:07:06.503
and never really change your
behavior because, essentially,

01:07:06.503 --> 01:07:07.170
you never learn.

01:07:07.170 --> 01:07:09.180
You never even pay
attention to any information

01:07:09.180 --> 01:07:13.400
that you might have available
that says your model is wrong.